 51: cdef class Convolve:#with gy cache


 52:     """


 53:     Make convolution from supplied **f** and **g**. If your functions are


 54:     analytically convolutable you will be better off implementing


 55:     analytically. This functor is implemented using numerical integration with


 56:     bound there are numerical issue that will, in most cases, lightly affect


 57:     normalization.s


 58: 


 59:     Argument from **f** and **g** is automatically merge by name. For example,


 60: 


 61:     ::


 62: 


 63:         f = lambda x, a, b, c: a*x**2+b*x+c


 64:         g = lambda x, a, sigma: gaussian(x,a,sigma)


 65:         h = Convolve(f,g,gbound)


 66:         describe(h)#['x','a','b','c','sigma']


 67: 


 68:         #h is equivalent to


 69:         def h_equiv(x, a, b, c, sigma):


 70:             return Integrate(f(x-t, a, b, c)*g(x, a, b, c), t_range=gbound)


 71: 


 72:     .. math::


 73: 


 74:         \\text{Convolve(f,g)}(t, arg \ldots) =


 75:                 \int_{\\tau \in \\text{gbound}}


 76:                 f(t-\\tau, arg \ldots)\\times g(t, arg\ldots) \, \mathrm{d}\\tau


 77: 


 78:     **Argument**


 79: 


 80:         - **f** Callable object, PDF.


 81:         - **g** Resolution function.


 82:         - **gbound** Bound of the resolution. Supplied something such that


 83:           g(x,*arg) is near 0 at the edges. Current implementation is


 84:           multiply reverse slide add straight up from the definition so this


 85:           bound is important. Overbounding is recommended.


 86:         - **nbins** Number of bins in multiply reverse slide add. Default(1000)


 87: 


 88:     .. note::


 89: 


 90:         You may be worried about normalization. By the property of convolution:


 91: 


 92:         .. math::


 93: 


 94:             \int_{\mathbf{R}^d}(f*g)(x) \, dx=\left(\int_{\mathbf{R}^d}f(x) \, dx\\right)\left(\int_{\mathbf{R}^d}g(x) \, dx\\right).


 95: 


 96:         This means if you convolute two normalized distributions you get back


 97:         a normalized distribution. However, since we are doing numerical


 98:         integration here we will be off by a little bit.


 99: 


 100:     """
